T he FORMAZIONE project, promoted by "Ferrante Aporti" Cooperativa Sociale,in collaboration with partners, is the result of a careful analysis of the Apulia region and overall of southern Italy .It has been found, a great acceleration of the economic crisis, often caused the lack of social inclusion for those individuals with special needs arising from a situation of social, family, economic disadvantage, that despite having a qualification or a vocational training defined struggling to find a work placement. .La Coop. Aporti, has been active for over ten years, managing services in favour of Families, minors, persons physically challenged persons,potential young offenders and senior citizens; Following adequate cultural and linguistic training,the project aims to offer the opportunity of  work experience abroad, to persons coming from a disadvantaged social backgrounds or those with "special needs":aiming to their needs of social and work inclusion.The previous experience of the project FORM-AZIONE, which has included more than 800 nominations, showed that young people residing in Apulia require very significant experience  in terms of personal, cultural and professional activation. An area need-analysis has led to the underscoring of six beneficiary groups:

1) Disabled-(individuals with physical disabilities and / or mental, waiting to start a career after earning a qualification and placed in pathways into employment or work placement protected / targeted); 

2) young graduates with no work experience-(young people who have achieved a diploma with various difficulties and with low skills base available to training in the 12 months following the award of the diploma); 

3) students from vocational schools and training institutions; 

4) subjects in the course of training from local farms; 

5) individuals with qualifications achieved and just recently spent on the labor market; 

6) subjects from addictions and paths included in vocational training courses.

The abovementioned protagonists of the project of FORMAZIONE are 100 people coming mostly from the municipalities and Territorial Areas of Apulia. In this context,the opportunity to offer them a professional on-site job experience means activating an otherwise significant experience both in terms of individual participant empowerment and expendability within the job market - not only those skills eventually learnt but also by way of future benefits in terms of psychological rewards as well as those of personal activation brought about by positive experience. The work experiences are often autonomy opportunities that allow  to develop their potentialities and  to participate actively in the growth of the EU membership. therefore it encourages the widespread and systematic series of actions to be able to build links between the needs and situations of fragility with the need to capture and conquest of the welfare conditions and concrete opportunities for integration in the world of production . The job experience in a work context tailored to participant characteristic/skills and chosen with a view to mobility by the sending organization, the intermediary organization and the candidat. Following an agreed programme:personal empowerment activities, cultural activities  (preparatory, cultural,linguistic and web-based activities ), knowledge of the work placements countries United Kingdom and Spain.

The reason for developing a transnational mobility project has its roots in a series of indicators that are the obvious symptoms of the social and economic changes of this historical moment. Sarno, like all of the Agro Nocerino Sarnese territory, presents an economic framework deteriorated by the crisis, with an unemployment rate of 20.4% (Source Ancitel-Comuniverso 2014), and an immigration rate of 4.69% (Source ISTAT 2014 ).
The socio-economic and cultural background of the Institute's students is of a low medium level and about 40% of them live in severe economic hardship. Even more serious are the difficult conditions of a 4.6% of students coming from the regions of North Africa and Eastern European countries. This situation affects early school drop-out. Here as follows, the numbers that attest how many students have dropped out of school during the 2014/2015 academic year: 4.2% in first classes (4% Campania), 4.4% in second classes (2.3% Campania), 2.9% in third classes (2.9% Campania), 2.1% in fourth classes (3.2% Campania), 2.4%, in fifth classes. The percentage left managed to endure until the final year.
The Fermi-Dorso Institute, through the project "M.I.D.E. – Metodologie Innovative Didattiche Europee- innovative European didactic methodologies ”, will work to adapt and innovate the teaching methods and the learning paths used within the Institute, and improve the approach used by the school to address the problem of early school leaving.
The project will involve 30 participants (27 teachers and 3 selected among the ATA staff within the Institute) which will undertake job shadowing activities, for a period of 15 days, in France, at the Association Européenne de l'Education de France-AEDE, in UK at Language Link London and in Spain at the Institut Bernat el Ferrer.
The main purposes of this project can be summarized as follows:
• adapting the education system to European standards;
• improving and expanding the language skills of the teachers and staff involved in the project;
• strengthening the international dimension of IISS "Fermi-Dorso";
• promoting initiatives to counteract early school leaving;
• raising European sense of belonging, knowledge of the European political project and of active European citizenship.
Specifically, the project aims at:
• developing the Institute's ability to use innovative teaching methodologies, tools and new educational approaches, and to adapt them to the special needs of different students;
• improving teachers’’ social skills, necessary for the creation of positive relationships with the students and within the classroom;
• stimulating teachers’ motivation, creativity and continuous professional development;
•  bringing the teachers closer to the CLIL methodology;
• making participants aware of their role and encouraging them to reflect on their teaching practice in order to identify both strengths and any possible  critical issues, and to promote actions to contrast early school leaving;
• promoting collaboration among teachers within the Institute;
• triggering a sharing mechanism to enhance dialogue and cooperation with parents, local institutions and the local production system.
For the 30 beneficiaries of the project M.I.D.E., the training experience acquired abroad will represent an opportunity to: improve social skills; learn new teaching methodologies and training programs; increase the ability to identify the critical issues related to learning disabilities and adapt their communication style; increase their skills in classroom management strategies and relationships with students.
The M.I.D.E project will have special significance in terms of impact on the students and on the entire  Institute through :
• the improvement of students’ personal development, from their preparation and involvement to  general school activities;
• the activation of strategies to face the phenomenon of early school leaving;
• the education improvement through the use of innovative teaching methods, which aim at creating a school environment in which students can feel understood and supported;
• Scholastic Institute internationalization which aims at offering training proposals in line with the needs of students and the demands of the European labor market.
It is estimated that the rate of early school leaving of the Institute may decrease in the years after the project, and settle at an average rate of 1.5%, compared with the initial average rate that, in the school year 2014/2015, was of 3.4%.
